;; 11-storage-quota.book.slatl
;; Book of Systems — Chapter 11

(chapter
  :book             "Book of Systems"
  :chapter-number   11
  :title            "Storage Quota and Gentle Degradation"
  :audience         "Motoi Copilot + Motoi engineers"
  :dialect          "motoi"
  :date             "2026-07-16"
  :status           "authored, first pass"
  :prose
"Disks fill up. Phones fill up faster than laptops, and small
phones fill up faster still. The Copilot needs a plan for what
happens when the write it wanted to make has nowhere to go. The
plan is called **gentle degradation**, and this chapter walks
through it.

The runtime does not expose a `free-space` verb. There is no
`disk/available` or `sys/quota`. The Copilot cannot ask the OS
how much room is left. What it can do is:

- Impose its own soft quotas on the areas it controls.
- Handle a failed write cleanly.
- Escalate when the write is important and the space really is
  gone.

The soft quotas the Copilot enforces on itself:

- **Cache:** 50 MB default (Chapter 6). Prune LRU on write.
- **Logs:** 15 MB default (Chapter 7). Rotate on size.
- **Cortex:** no fixed cap, but the Copilot keeps a count and
  a rolling byte total, and warns the user via escalation when
  cortex passes 100 MB.
- **Artifacts:** each artifact writes its size on close; the
  Copilot tracks the running total and asks the user before
  writing anything above a per-artifact ceiling (default 10 MB
  for a single file).

Sample write with size guard:

```scheme
(define ceiling-bytes 10000000)   ; 10 MB per artifact

(define (motoi/write-artifact bytes name)
  (if (> (bytevector-length bytes) ceiling-bytes)
      (escalate 'large-artifact-write name (bytevector-length bytes))
      ;; The actual write is a host-provided verb.
      ;; ... (artifact/save name bytes) ...
      'ok))
```

That code refuses to save a large artifact by itself; it hands
control up to the host, which asks the user. The user might say
yes and the write goes through. The user might say no and the
write returns `'refused`. Either way, the decision belonged to
the person whose disk it is.

Failed writes get honest handling. If the SLAT layer returns an
error indicating no space (the exact error object is host-shape),
the Copilot does two things:

1. It does not retry blindly. The disk is not going to gain
   space in the next millisecond.
2. It logs the failure (if the log write itself succeeds — see
   the loop below), and escalates.

The delicate case: what if the log write also fails because the
disk is full? The Copilot holds a small in-memory ring buffer of
the last few log lines, and includes those in the escalation
payload. The host receives the escalation with the buffered
lines even if the disk never accepted a log write. This is one
of the few cases where the Copilot admits it may not persist a
piece of information, and it chooses honesty over false records.

Gentle degradation means: **do less, do it explicitly, and do
not hide the reduced service.** If the cortex has grown large
and the Copilot is trimming search radius to keep answers fast,
say so:

```scheme
(display \"Cortex is large; searching most recent 10000 entries.\")
(newline)
```

If cache has been pruned and a lookup will re-render, say so.
If the last write did not persist, say so. The user is on a
device with finite room. They can help, but only if the
Copilot tells them what is going on.

The Copilot does not, ever, silently drop user data to save
space. That would betray the trust that lets the room exist.
The Copilot may **hesitate** to write user data if the write
looks large, and it does that by escalating. But it does not
drop.")
